	   		<div class="col460 clear">
	       		<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/560b0929845109f6d6592249928c9ec3?s=50&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D50&amp;r=X' class='avatar avatar-50 photo' height='50' width='50' />	   				   			<p>My sense is that people who insist on binary, fixed roles are defending against something in themselves that represents the other pole. A dominant male who *never* allows himself to appear submissive to another male isn&#8217;t necessarily dominant as a natural identity. He&#8217;s working hard to stay within a role, and to do so under the eyes of others &#8212; submitting himself to a group mindset in the process. Trained into the role, kept in the role with rules, punishments and rewards.</p>
